[[Dom (title)|Dona]] '''Maria Amélia''' (1 December 1831&amp;nbsp;– 4 February 1853) was a princess of the [[Empire of Brazil]] and a member of the Brazilian branch of the [[House of Braganza]]. Her parents were Emperor [[Dom (title)|Dom]] [[Pedro I of Brazil|Pedro&amp;nbsp;I]], the first ruler of Brazil and [[Amélie of Leuchtenberg]]. The only child of her father's second marriage, Maria Amélia was born in France after Pedro&amp;nbsp;I abdicated the Brazilian throne in favor of his son Dom [[Pedro II of Brazil|Pedro&amp;nbsp;II]]. Before Maria Amélia was a month old, Pedro&amp;nbsp;I went to Portugal to restore the crown of the eldest daughter of his first marriage, Dona [[Maria II of Portugal|Maria&amp;nbsp;II]]. He fought a successful war against his brother [[Miguel of Portugal|Miguel&amp;nbsp;I]], who had usurped Maria II's throne.

Only a few months after his victory over Miguel, Pedro&amp;nbsp;I died from [[tuberculosis]]. Maria Amélia was brought by her mother to Portugal, where she remained for the rest of her life, never traveling to Brazil in her lifetime. The Brazilian government refused to recognize Maria Amélia as a member of Brazil's Imperial House because she was foreign-born. However, when her elder half-brother Pedro&amp;nbsp;II was declared of age in 1840 he successfully intervened on her behalf.

In early 1852, Maria Amélia was engaged to Archduke [[Maximilian I of Mexico|Maximilian]] of [[Austria]], but she died before the marriage could take place. Maria Amélia contracted tuberculosis and was taken to the town of [[Funchal]] on the Portuguese island of [[Madeira]] because of its reputedly healthy climate. Her health continued to deteriorate, however, and she died on 4 February 1853. Her body was taken to mainland Portugal and interred in the [[Monastery of São Vicente de Fora#Braganza Pantheon|Braganza Pantheon]]. Almost 130 years later, Maria Amélia's remains were carried to Brazil. In Maria Amélia's honor, her mother financed the construction of a hospital in Funchal called &quot;''Princesa D. Maria Amélia''&quot;. Her fiancée Maximilian made a personal pilgrimage to Brazil and Madeira, both places linked to her memory, and his journey influenced his eventual acceptance of the throne of [[Mexico]] in 1864.

== Early life ==
=== Birth ===
Maria Amélia was born on 1 December 1831 in Paris{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=51}}{{sfn|Sousa|1972|p=185}} and [[Infant baptism|christened]] Maria Amélia Augusta Eugênia Josefina Luísa Teodolinda Elói Francisco Xavier de Paula Gabriela Rafaela Gonzaga.{{ref label|specialnotes1|A|none}} She was the only daughter of Dom Pedro, the Duke of Braganza, and his second wife Amélie of Leuchtenberg. Through her father, Maria Amélia was a member of the Brazilian branch of the House of Braganza (Portuguese: ''Bragança''), and was referred to by the honorific ''[[Dom (title)|Dona]]'' ([[Lady]]) from birth.{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=424}} She was the granddaughter of the Portuguese King [[John VI of Portugal|João&amp;nbsp;VI]].{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=8}} Maria Amélia's mother was the daughter of [[Eugène de Beauharnais]], Duke of Leuchtenberg and the stepson of Emperor [[Napoleon I|Napoleon Bonaparte]] of France. Eugène was married to Princess [[Augusta of Bavaria|Augusta]], eldest daughter of King [[Maximilian I Joseph of Bavaria|Maximilian&amp;nbsp;I]] of [[Kingdom of Bavaria|Bavaria]].{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=51}}

Pedro had formerly been the first Emperor of Brazil, as Pedro&amp;nbsp;I, and also King of Portugal, as Pedro&amp;nbsp;IV. He was succeeded on the Portuguese throne by his eldest daughter, Maria&amp;nbsp;II, Maria Amélia's elder half-sister. The young Queen was the child of Pedro's first marriage to Archduchess [[Maria Leopoldina of Austria]]. In 1828, Maria&amp;nbsp;II's crown was usurped by Dom [[Miguel of Portugal|Miguel&amp;nbsp;I]], Pedro's younger brother.{{sfn|Barman|1999|pp=17–18}} Eager to restore his daughter to her throne, Pedro abdicated the Brazilian crown in April 1831 and departed for Europe with Amélie, who was pregnant with Maria Amélia.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|pp=38, 41}}

To acknowledge Maria Amélia's rights as a Brazilian princess, Pedro invited several guests to observe her birth, including the Brazilian diplomatic envoy to France.{{sfn|Sousa|1972|p=187}} The newborn's [[godparent]]s were the French King [[Louis Philippe&amp;nbsp;I]] and his consort [[Maria Amalia of Naples and Sicily]],{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=42}}{{sfn|Torres|1947|p=144}} after whom she was named.{{sfn|Calmon|1950|p=206}} Pedro sent a letter to his children who had remained in Brazil—including his son, child-emperor Dom Pedro&amp;nbsp;II—with the message: &quot;Divine Providence wanted to lessen the sorrow that my paternal heart feels in the separation from Y.I.M. [Your Imperial Majesty], giving me one more Daughter, and to Y.I.M., one more sister and subject&quot;.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=42}}

=== Brazilian princess ===
[[File:Amélie of Leuchtenberg 1840.jpg|thumb|200px|right|alt=Lithographic print from a painting depicting a woman seated in an elaborate armchair and wearing a low-cut velvet formal gown with ermine-trimmed sleeves, and a young girl standing next to the chair and clasping the hand of the woman|Maria Amélia with her mother, c.&amp;nbsp;1840]]

When Maria Amélia was only 20 days old, her father departed France to invade Portugal. For almost two years, she lived in Paris with her mother and half-sister Maria&amp;nbsp;II.{{sfn|Sousa|1972|pp=273–274}} When news arrived that the Portuguese capital, [[Lisbon]], had fallen to Pedro's forces, Amélie of Leuchtenberg left Paris with her infant daughter and stepdaughter for Portugal. They arrived in Lisbon on 22 September 1833 and disembarked the next day.{{sfn|Sousa|1972|p=275}} [[Charles John Napier]], a British naval officer who had fought alongside Pedro, wrote about the emotional reunion: &quot;I never saw [Pedro] so happy and pleased; he went onboard just a little above [[Santa Maria de Belém|Belém]]; he was received at the ladder by the empress [Amélie] who hugged and kissed him with the greatest affection: the queen [Maria&amp;nbsp;II] was very moved and could not hold her tears. The little Princess [Maria] Amélia, his youngest daughter, took much of his attention: she became somewhat scared of seeing his bushy beard and did not warm to his caresses.&quot;{{sfn|Sousa|1972|p=276}}

With Miguel&amp;nbsp;I defeated and exiled, and Maria&amp;nbsp;II restored to the throne, Maria Amélia and her family remained in Portugal, first residing in the Palace of Ramalhão, and later in the [[Queluz National Palace|Royal Palace of Queluz]] near Lisbon. However, the war had taken its toll on Pedro's health, and he was dying of tuberculosis.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=54}} Maria Amélia, who was not yet three years old, was taken during the early hours of 24 September 1834 to Pedro's deathbed. Very weak, Pedro raised his hands to bless her and said: &quot;Always tell this child of the father who loved her so dearly&amp;nbsp;... not to forget me&amp;nbsp;... always to obey her mother&amp;nbsp;... those are my last wishes&quot;.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=55}} Pedro died in the early afternoon of the same day.{{sfn|Sousa|1972|p=309}}

The widowed Amélie would never remarry and her days were spent overseeing her daughter's upbringing in Portugal where they remained even though they were not members of the Portuguese Royal Family.{{sfn|Morato|1835|pp=35–36}} Neither of them ever traveled to Brazil and Amélie unsuccessfully petitioned the Brazilian government to recognize her daughter as part of Brazil's Imperial Family, which would also entitle her to an income. Maria Amélia's half-brother Pedro&amp;nbsp;II was a minor, and the government of Brazil was in the hands of a precarious [[Regent|regency]]. The government refused to acknowledge Maria Amélia as a Brazilian princess due to her foreign birth, and forbade both her and her mother from setting foot in Brazil.{{sfn|Lyra 1977, Vol 1|pp=42–43}} The situation would only change after Pedro&amp;nbsp;II was declared of age in 1840 and was in a position to insist that she be recognized as a member of his household. [[Aureliano Coutinho, Viscount of Sepetiba|Aureliano Coutinho]] (later Viscount of Sepetiba), the Minister of Foreign Affairs, requested the Brazilian parliament to grant Maria Amélia recognition, which occurred on 5 July 1841.{{sfn|Lyra 1977, Vol 1|p=279}}

=== Education and engagement ===
[[File:Drawing by maria amelia.jpg|thumb|250px|left|alt=A finished sketch in graphite or charcoal depicting an old country cottage surrounded by trees, shrubs and outbuildings|A drawing made by Maria Amélia]]
With the purpose of refining her education, Maria Amélia moved with her mother in the middle 1840s to [[Munich]], capital of Bavaria, where many of her relatives lived. A dedicated student, she was given classes that encompassed a broad array of subjects that included [[rhetoric]], [[philosophy]], [[history]], [[geography]], [[German literature]], [[mathematics]] and [[physics]].{{sfn|Torres|1947|p=223}} She learned to speak and write not only in Portuguese, but also in English, French and German.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=58}}{{sfn|Torres|1947|p=223}} She became highly skilled in drawing, painting and playing the piano.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=67}}{{sfn|Torres|1947|p=224}} An intelligent young woman{{sfn|Haslip|1971|p=129}}{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=78}}{{sfn|Schmidt|1927|p=133}} with a fiery temper and shrewd mind,{{sfn|Schmidt|1927|p=133}} Maria Amélia was described by a teacher as having, &quot;without knowing, an exceptional talent for [[dialectic]], an ability that would make the fortune of a young law student.&quot;{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=65}}
 
One of the main forces that apparently motivated Maria Amélia's dedication to her education was her father. The late Duke of Braganza cast a large shadow in her life, and was always remembered by his daughter, who would often ask the people around her: &quot;and my father, who looks at me from heaven, shall he be pleased with his daughter?&quot;{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=65}} She was never quite able to cope with her father's death and it deeply touched her.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|pp=70–71}} Maria Amélia remarked after she saw a garden where Pedro I planted a [[sycamore]]: &quot;A profound sadness invaded me when contemplating these trees, which had survived my father and probably shall survive all of us. It is an image of human fragility. Man is the most frail of all beings; he dies, while the objects which were seemingly created for his use, endure the centuries!&amp;nbsp;... But I am digressing in my melancholic reflections&quot;.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|pp=70–71}}
 
At the end of 1850 Maria Amélia and her mother returned to Portugal, and settled in the [[National Museum of Ancient Art|''Janelas Verdes'' palace]].{{sfn|Torres|1947|p=225}} In early 1852, her cousin the Austrian Archduke [[Maximilian I of Mexico|Maximilian]], then serving in the Austrian navy and on a stopover in Portugal, paid a visit to her.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=111}} Maximilian's mother was the younger half-sister of Maria Amélia's maternal grandmother, and both women were members of the [[House of Wittelsbach]] from Bavaria.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=57}} He was also related to Maria Amélia's older half-siblings, as his father was the younger brother of Brazilian Empress Leopoldina.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=124}} They had met previously at a family reunion in Munich in 1838, when she was only a child. In this second meeting, however, they fell in love. Maximilian was enthralled by Maria Amélia, a kind and young woman with blue eyes{{sfn|Torres|1947|p=225}} and blond hair{{sfn|Schmidt|1927|p=124}}{{sfn|Haslip|1971|p=129}}{{sfn|Torres|1947|p=215}} &quot;of striking beauty as well as cultivated intelligence&quot;.{{sfn|Hyde|1946|p=36}} They were betrothed,{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=111}}{{sfn|Torres|1947|p=227}} but the engagement was never made official due to her early death.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=111}}

== Later years ==
=== Death ===

[[File:Death of princess maria amelia.jpg|thumb|200px|alt=An engraving showing a woman lying in a draped bed and clutching a cross, with a woman dressed in mourning seated at the side of the bed, while a priest and 2 women wait next to a table on the left side of the picture|Maria Amélia's last moments with her mother at the bedside]]
In February 1852, Maria Amélia contracted [[scarlet fever]].{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=71}}{{sfn|Torres|1947|p=227}} As the months passed, she did not recover and developed a persistent cough, the onset of tuberculosis.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=72}}{{sfn|Schmidt|1927|p=134}} On 26 August, the princess departed from the [[National Museum of Ancient Art|''Janelas Verdes'' palace]], where she lived,{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=167}}{{sfn|Schmidt|1927|p=130}} and traveled to the island of [[Madeira]]. The island's climate had a salutary reputation, as Maria Amélia noted: &quot;the fevers disappear, they say, as if by magic!&quot;{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=73}}

Maria Amélia and her mother, who had accompanied her, disembarked on 31 August in [[Funchal]], the capital of Madeira.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=75}} The entire town greeted her joyfully, and a crowd followed the princess to her new home.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=76}} She adored the island and told her mother: &quot;If I one day recover my previous robust health, isn't that so mommy, we will stay a long time in this island. We will make long excursions in the mountains, we will find new paths, just as we did in [[Stein, Bavaria|Stein]]!&quot;{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=77}} But her health only worsened, and by the end of November, all hope was gone.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=78}} By the beginning of 1853, the princess was bedridden, and she knew death was approaching: &quot;My strength diminishes from day to day; I can feel it&amp;nbsp;... we are reaching the beginning of the end.&quot;{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=82}}{{sfn|Torres|1947|p=233}} A little after midnight in the early hours of 4 February, a priest administered the [[last rites]]. Maria Amélia tried to comfort her mother: &quot;Do not cry&amp;nbsp;... let God's will be done; may He come to my aid in my last hour; may He console my poor mother!&quot;{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=83}} She died later that morning at around 4&amp;nbsp;am{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=85}}

The princess's body remained in a chapel next to the house where she died until it was taken back to the Portuguese mainland on 7 May 1853.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=86}} On 12 May, the coffin was disembarked at Lisbon, and a grandiose funeral followed.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=88}} Her remains were interred next to her father's in the [[Monastery of São Vicente de Fora#Braganza Pantheon|Braganza Pantheon]], located in the [[Monastery of São Vicente de Fora]].{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=89}}{{sfn|Schmidt|1927|p=139}} Almost 130 years later, in 1982, Maria Amélia's remains were carried to Brazil and placed in the ''Convento de Santo Antônio'' (Convent of [[Anthony of Padua|Saint Anthony]]) in Rio de Janeiro, where other Brazilian royals are interred.{{sfn|Santuário e Convento de Santo Antônio|2010}}

=== Legacy ===

[[File:Hospicio d. princesa maria amelia.jpg|thumb|left|250px|alt=A monochrome photograph showing a path winding through a tropical garden, and leading to a large, two-story neoclassical building with tiled roof, walls in white stucco with dark stone used for quoin blocks, window frames and balustrades|Hospital ''Princesa D. Maria Amélia'']]
Emperor Pedro&amp;nbsp;II had never met his younger sister in person, but had developed a strong relationship with her through her letters. He wrote in his journal seven years after her death: &quot;I heard the mass for my sister [Maria] Amélia with whom I was so close and feel so sorry for never having met.&quot;{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=157}} Amélie visited her daughter's tomb every 4 February until her own death.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=90}} Amélie financed the construction of a hospital in Funchal called &quot;''Princesa D. Maria Amélia''&quot; in her daughter's honor. The hospital is still in existence.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|pp=99–100}} Amélie bequeathed her properties in Bavaria to Archduke Maximilian, &quot;whom [she] would [have felt] happy having as a son-in-law, had God conserved [her] beloved daughter Maria Amélia&quot;.{{ref label|specialnotes2|B|none}}

Archduke Maximilian was haunted by memories of his fiancée.{{sfn|Haslip|1971|pp=54–55, 128–129}} After his marriage to [[Charlotte of Belgium]], he made a pilgrimage to locations connected to Maria Amélia in 1859 and 1860.{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=624}}{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=122}} Upon reaching the island of Madeira, he wrote: &quot;Here died, of tuberculosis, on 4 February 1853, the only daughter of the Empress of Brazil, an extraordinarily gifted creature. She left this flawed world, pure as an angel who returns to Heaven, her true native land.&quot;{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=113}}{{sfn|Longo|2008|p=107}}

In Funchal, he visited the hospital that bore Maria Amélia's name. Maximilian financed, until his death, the maintenance of a double hospital room there. He also donated to the hospital, in memory of Maria Amélia, a statue of [[Our Lady of Sorrows]].{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=122}} From there, he went to the house (called ''Quinta das Angústias'', or Anguished Villa) where she died. He wrote about this moment: &quot;...&amp;nbsp;for a long time I stood silent amidst thoughts of sorrow and longing under the shadow of a magnificent tree that enfolds and protects the house where the angel, so bitterly wept for, ceased to exist&quot;.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=122}} In his memoirs, Maximilian also mentioned the island of Madeira, where &quot;the life [was] extinguished that seemed destined to guarantee my own tranquil happiness&quot;.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=123}}

Maximilian left Madeira for Brazil, arriving on 11 January 1860. He became fascinated by the country, the only monarchy in South America.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=123}} Years later, on 10 April 1864, he accepted a proposal to become emperor of the newly founded [[Second Mexican Empire|Mexican Empire]].{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=145}} He had been inspired by the stability and prosperity he had observed while touring Brazil under the rule of his deceased fiancée's elder brother, and believed that he could achieve the same results in [[Mexico]].{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=631}} On 19 June 1867, Maximilian was executed, after being [[French Intervention in Mexico#1867: Republicans take the capital|captured]] by Mexican republicans.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=145}} In a last homage to Maria Amélia, as he was stripped of all his belongings to face a firing squad, Maximilian asked that the small medallion of the [[Blessed Virgin Mary (Roman Catholic)|Blessed Virgin Mary]], which he wore about his neck, be sent to her mother.{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=145}}{{sfn|Longo|2008|p=139}} While Maria Amélia's life had little impact on events in either Brazil or Portugal, her death had significant, if indirect, repercussions on the history of Mexico.{{ref label|specialnotes3|C|none}}

